Hercules leaves Thebes after killing his sons
because of the madness inflicted by Juno
and comes to Tarentum
where he seeks employment as coactor
to forget his crimes away from death and with a decent wage.
He enters the service of a bad moneylender
and starts collecting interests from various loans.
He makes a big impression with his job-adequate qualities.
He himself professes liking the job and being happy again
largely ignoring the bad aspects of it.
The next household he goes to is that of a young guy
who took a loan in his father's absence
to help a poor foreign girl he fell in love with pay for her mother's funeral.
He makes an impression on Hercules and successfully negociates a delay
(while still having no means to repay even with the delay)
Checking on his girl afterwards for some comfort
he discovers her with chatting with a rival
and after she is alone decided to confront her.
but she savagely rejects him and makes fun of him denying ever even seeing him.
Heartbroken he gives up all hope and when Hercules comes back he asks him
to just finish him rather than torturing him anymore since he won't get any moneylender
from him anyway. Hercules refuses and softened by the tale of madness
decides to help his newfound comrade.
Heated discussions follow between the two rivals and while fighting is building up,
the rival flees to the girl house for protection.
Exceeded the old servant of the girls speaks up as a negociator.
She recognizes Hercules and asks him to protect his girl rather than defend some
random lover's claim.
The girl is thus discovered to have a twin sister
and the two sisters to be Hercules' daughters from recently dead heartbroken Megara.
Subsequently Hercules tells the complaining moneylender off,
the two rivals making peace and the wedding of the two sisters
take place following the return of the young guy's father.